sec.p:

Fusarium oxysporum

f. sp. 
dianthi
(
Fod
) is the causal agent of vascular wilting of 

Dianthus caryophyllus

L. (
Caryophyllaceae
), commonly called as carnation. This phytopathogen constitutes the most devastating disease of the carnation crop worldwide. The frequent presence of this pathogen in soils used for carnation cultivation causes major economic losses when susceptible cultivars are grown in greenhouses (

; 

). Despite the application of sanitary and cultural practices (e.g., substrate suppressiveness, clean growing surfaces, plant material and water, appropriate handling of rotation patterns, fertilization, and removal of diseased plants) to prevent the introduction and further dispersal of this pathogen in carnation crops, the occurrence of this disease has promoted interest in the development of new efficient control methods (

; 

). Endogenous antifungal-based resistance modulation represents an ecofriendly alternative for the control of this disease (Shah

et al., 2020). In this regard, although the relationship between the presence and content of some endogenous specialized metabolites and the resistance level against 
Fod
has been previously determined in several studies, recent studies on this topic are limited. The information available until now indicates that 
Fod
-resistant carnation cultivars produce several antifungal compounds, such as anthranilate derivatives (e. g., dianthalexins) and phenolics (e.g., benzoic acids and flavonoids), against the pathogenic infection (

, 

; 

). However, accumulation of antifungal metabolites in carnation tissues depends on the plant part involved, since nitrogenous compounds usually accumulate in stems (

), whereas phenolics appear to be preferably accumulated in roots (

).

The role of flavonoids in plant defense has been reviewed (

; 

; 

), and these compounds have been proposed to be associated with antimicrobial and even antioxidant activity (

, 

; 

). These compounds can be used by plants to regulate the levels of highly reactive oxygen species (ROS) during infection of necrotrophic pathogens (

; 

). For biotrophic pathogens, flavonoids have been suggested to be mainly associated with antifungal activity and modulation of hormonal responses to generate a more effective response to the pathogen (

). In general, the role of these naturally occurring compounds in resistance depends on several variables such as the plant genotype, the environmental conditions, and the pathogen lifestyle (Gorniak´et al., 2019; 

; 

; 

).

The presence of antifungal flavonoids against Fod in carnation has attracted the attention of researchers because these compounds have been isolated from healthy and inoculated plant parts and tissues of resistant carnation cultivars. A previous study reported that inoculated plants of the Fod -resistant ‘Novada ’ carnation cultivar exhibited increased accumulation of kaempferide 3- O -[2 G -β- D- glucopyranosyl]- β- rutinoside in both stems and roots for 10 days after inoculation (
,
). The anti- Fod fungitoxic effect of this constitutive flavonol glycoside in this cultivar has also been reported (
). Other Fod -resistant carnation cultivars (i.e., ‘ Roland ’) yielded fungitoxic flavonoids such as quercetin 3- O -α- L- arabinopyranosyl-(1 → 6)-β- D- glucopyranoside (peltatoside) and 3,5,7,2 ′ -tetrahydroxyflavone (datiscetin) from healthy and inoculated in vitro -generated calli and parent plants (
). Other flavonoids such as apigenin 6, 8-di- C -β- D- glucopyranoside, kaempferol 3- O -β- D- glucopyranosyl-(1 → 2)- O -[α- L- rhamnopyranosyl-(1 → 6)]-β- D- glucopyranoside, and kaempferol 3- O -[α- L- rhamnopyranosyl-(1 → 6)]-β- D- glucopyranoside have also been described and quantified in several carnation cultivars (
). Additionally, roots of resistant cultivars were found to contain higher levels of flavonoids than those of susceptible cultivars (
).

The phenylpropanoid pathway is an important source of phenolic compounds, including flavonoids, in plants (

). In this pathway, a wide variety of enzymes play essential roles in regulating the levels of phenolic compounds. Accordingly, chalcone synthase (CHS) and chalcone isomerase (CHI) have been considered to be the control points for flavonoid biosynthesis (

; 

). While CHS (EC 2.3.1.74) catalyzes the condensation of three iterative malonyl-CoA units on 
p
-coumaroyl CoA, the final product of the phenylpropanoid pathway, to generate 4,2 
′
,4 
′
,6 
′
-tetrahydroxy-chalcone, CHI (EC 5.5.1.6) catalyzes the enantioselective intramolecular cyclization product of CHS to generate (
2S
)-naringenin, the basic structural core of flavonoids. These enzymes have been mainly studied in carnation in relation to flavonoid biosynthesis in carnation petals (

; 

). Flavonol synthase (FLS, EC 1.14.20.6) is also an important contributor to the flavonoid biosynthetic pathway. It catalyzes the regioselective desaturation of dihydroflavonols to produce flavonols through the formation of a double bond between C2 and C3 at the C-ring (

). Flavonols are an important group of flavonoids and perform various biological functions such as protection against UV, transport of auxins, and protection against pathogens (Gorniak´et al., 2019; 

). In fact, flavonol-type compounds are mostly described in carnation and are commonly associated with resistance against phytopathogens (

). Another important checkpoint involved in the regulation of flavonoid biosynthesis is related to the V-myb myeloblastosis viral oncogene homolog (MYB) transcription factor (TF) family, such as MYB11, 12, and 111 (also recognized as PFG2, 1, and 3, respectively) (

). These TFs are highly dependent on tissue 
type
and respond to external signals, e.g., elicitors or UV radiation (

; 

). MYB TFs have also been characterized in model plants, such as 

Zea mays

(corn), 

Arabidopsis thaliana

, and 

Petunia
spp.

(

; 

), but there is no information regarding these TFs for carnation.

Activation of the biosynthetic pathway for a specific metabolite at the early phase of pathogen infection is a key point influencing the role of these pathways in resistance (
;
). In carnation, the current evidence for flavonoid biosynthesis associated with Fod resistance includes the differential expression of genes encoding proteins involved in the biosynthetic pathway. Thus, the differential constitutive expression of these two flavonoid biosynthesis enzymes (i.e., CHS and CHI) in the roots of cuttings from susceptible and resistant cultivars (
), as well as the isolation of specific fungitoxic flavonoids from the roots of resistant cultivars (
,
,
), have been previously explored. However, holistic evaluations of the differential accumulation of these compounds and molecular evidence for the dynamics of flavonoid biosynthesis in carnation roots in response to Fod inoculation are limited. Therefore, as a part of our research on carnation– Fod interaction, we investigated the differential flavonoid accumulation responses and the expression of biosynthetic genes during the interaction with this pathogen in carnation roots, and then evaluated the differences between resistant/susceptible and constitutive/inoculated pairs. The results confirmed the importance of flavonoid-related production and accumulation within those roles in the resistance of carnation against Fod.

The changes in total phenolic content (TPC) and total flavonoid content (TFC) constitute a first-line approach to determine the early changes occurring in flavonoid biosynthesis (
). During the 96-h in vivo assay, carnation plants effectively exhibited variations in TPC and TFC at different levels. For the TPC of the two cultivars with and without Fod inoculation, values were found to be in the range of 50–210 μg of gallic acid equivalents (GAE) per g fresh weight (fw) of plant material ( Fig. 3a ). However, the constitutive TPC values showed significant differences between cultivars; therefore, GRC yielded an average value of 100 μg GAE/g fw, whereas MSC afforded 50 μg GAE/g fw. These results coincided with the values reported for nine carnation cultivars grown and commercialized in Colombia with contrasting levels of resistance to Fod (
).

These results additionally agreed with the findings of a previous study, in which pathogen inoculation caused variations in certain phenolic compounds evaluated by high-performance liquid chromatography (HPLC) (

). However, this study reported a phenolics-based increase only at 96 h post-inoculation (hpi), since plants collected at earlier times showed no variations. In the present study, pathogen inoculation in 
GRC
caused a significant increase in the TPC at the same time (96 hpi), while 
MSC
exhibited no effects of 
Fod
inoculation on both TPC and TFC at all test times. The phenolic compounds that were potentially accumulated included some glycosylated flavonoids and other cinnamic acid derivatives, which may be a part of the first-line chemical defense since they accumulate at the early phase after pathogen inoculation (

; 

; 

). Phenolic compounds are involved in complex phenomena associated with the strengthening of cell walls during pathogen response (Bell´es et al., 2008; 

; 

; 

). Thus, such compounds could be esterified with the polymeric carbohydrate components of the cell wall, decreasing its degradation by the cell wall-degrading enzymes (CWDEs) secreted by necrotrophic and hemibiotrophic pathogens (

). Thus, the increase in the levels of phenolic compounds at 96 hpi may be associated with the histological events reported in the roots of resistant carnation cultivars during pathogen inoculation (

). Phenolics may play a very important role in resistance to vascular wilt-causing pathogens, since they have direct antimicrobial activity, are constituents of polymeric vascular coatings (

), and have been associated with the extravascular defense by roots against 

Fusarium oxysporum
(
Pouralibaba et al., 2017
)

.

On the other hand, the TFC also showed some changes in the carnation plants evaluated in this study (
Fig. 3b
). TFC values were found to be in the range of 40–120 μg of catechin equivalents (CE) per g of fresh plant material (
Fig. 3
). Constitutive TFC expression showed similar behavior as that of TPC. 
GRC
showed higher average TFC values (i.e., 
70 mg
CE/gtw), which were significantly different from those of 
MSC
(i.e., 40 CE/gtw). These results also coincide with the findings of previous studies in other carnation cultivars (

), in which enhanced flavonoid contents were related to resistance against 
Fod
(

, 

, 

; 

). In fact, variations in the flavonoid contents of resistant cultivars and different tissues have been also reported for pathosystems involving 

Fusarium

pathogens (

; 

; 

; 

; 

). In addition, inoculation with 
Fod
race 2 causes a significant increase (

P

<
0.05

) in both TPC and TFC values at 96 hpi in 
GRC
roots, since such elevations were not observed in the respective controls, nor in the inoculated 
MSC
, at the same time (i.e., 96 hpi) (
Fig. 3a
). However, the TFC of inoculated 
GRC
roots exhibited a significant difference at 48 hpi in comparison to the non-inoculated plants. The increase in TFC after inoculation may be associated with the role of these metabolites in the regulation of reactive oxygen species (ROS) (

; Dumanovi´c et al., 2020), whose mechanism has been reported to be important for preventing activation of the necrotrophic pathogen phase (

).

Another widely reported function of flavonoids is related to their phytoalexin-based action (

; 

; 

). The role of flavonoids in carnation may be associated with antifungal activity (

, 

), but it is also related to their antioxidant activity (

; 

; 

; S´a et al., 2009). Accordingly, fluctuations in the oxidative balance caused by the pathogen infection promote a response related to the enhanced levels of these compounds (

; Dumanovic´et al., 2020; 

; 

). Since the antioxidant action is limited to plant tissue-related locations (

), the possibility that flavonoid-type compounds completely regulate the oxidative burst within the plant defense response cannot be ruled out. However, the inactivation of highly reactive oxygen species (ROS) is a response associated with resistance to necrotrophic pathogens. After recognition, these highly oxidizing species are not required in the same proportion and should be eliminated to avoid cell death. Such an event might favor the colonization by 

Fusarium

pathogens showing necrotrophic phases (

; Sa´et al., 2009). For this reason, accumulation of phenolic compounds and flavonoids is proposed to be a part of the basal plant response that could be associated with the horizontal or polygenic resistance presented by carnation against 
Fod
(

).

Variations in the chemical composition of the 54 raw extracts from carnation roots were also investigated by means of targeted metabolic profiling in order to expand the flavonoid characterization and distribution beyond TFC during Fod inoculation, and select the statistically top-ranked constitutively expressed and induced flavonoids in the carnation resistance response. LC-MS profiles were processed and the MS-derived features were then recovered from the raw profiles and labelled with the respective retention time–mass/charge ratio (rt/ m/z ) pairs. In total, 1235 negative ion mode-derived features were identified and subsequently filtered to compile specifically flavonoid-like metabolites according to the typical flavonoid bands I and II (i.e., 270–295 and 310–350 nm , respectively) in the UV spectra. After this filtering process, 96 filtered features (i.e., flavonoids) from 54 observations (i.e., samples) were gathered into a dataset to create a feature intensity table (FIT) and used to explore and analyze the metabolite changes under supervised statistics. The most important features ranked and selected by the statistical analysis were annotated at MSI level 2 (
) by using accurate mass and diagnostic MS fragment evidence. The rest of the features were annotated at MSI levels 3–4 or remained unannotated. The most statistically important annotated features exhibited quasimolecular ions above m/z 500 and triggered fragment ions at m/z 285, 301, and 315, indicating the presence of kaempferol, quercetin, and methylquercetin flavonols as aglycones, which was confirmed by the UV maximum absorptions at ca. 340 and 280 nm (i.e., bands I and II, respectively) for flavonols. Additionally, the presence of fragment ions at m/z 162, 146, 132 loses, which are the typical sugar fragments of glycosides for hexose (glucose), pentose (arabinose), and deoxyhexose (rhamnose) residues, respectively, and the deduced presence of ester substitutions (such as acetyl, galloyl, synapyl, feruroyl, and malyl) led to the compound annotation presented in Table 1 . In this regard, some authors suggested that the flavonoid glycosylation mediated by uridine diphosphate glucosyltransferase (UGT) enzymes played a significant role in responses to biotic stresses (
;
;
). However, while the addition of a particular glycosyl group does not directly influence the biological activity, it can indirectly improve other physicochemical properties to facilitate the action, such as transport and targeting (
).

