2.2.2.1. Metabolic profiling-based analysis of constitutive flavonoids from the roots of carnation cultivars.
An exploratory overview of these constitutive root flavonoids that are potentially relevant in discriminating the non-inoculated carnation cultivars studied herein was initially performed through univariate analysis. A paired fold change (FC) analysis was then conducted to compare the absolute change values between both cultivars for all the evaluated time-points, by using these two global categories as group means (i.e., GRC and MSC , gathering the different sampling times per cultivar) to classify the whole dataset. It was then pre-processed through log transformation and mean-centering (i.e., column-wise normalization) to calculate the ratio between group means. Thus, the number of GRC / MSC pairs with consistent change above or below |2| (as selected threshold) was counted, and the resulting pairs were expressed as log2 scale (FC). The significant features identified by FC analysis are presented in Fig. 4a . The number of significant features per cultivar was found to be 37 for GRC (red dots) and 9 for MSC (blue dots), indicating a global difference in the flavonoid composition between these cultivars. The existence of a higher number of significant flavonoid-related features in GRC can be firstly rationalized due to the genetic differences among GRC and MSC . However, other resistant cultivars were recognized to accumulate higher amounts of some metabolites and even more metabolites than susceptible cultivars, which were related to Fod resistance (
,
,
). In addition, as mentioned above, this accumulation may exhibit a time-dependent occurrence (
;
). Therefore, a principal component analysis (PCA) was performed to evaluate the flavonoid-based chemical differences along sampling times (0–96 h). The resulting three-dimensional (principal component 1 [PC1] vs. PC2 vs. PC3) score plot is presented in Fig. 4b . This score plot showed a particular clustering pattern, representing 81% of the explained variance. The earlier times (0 and 12 h) of both cultivars were grouped to form a single cluster, but the later times (24, 48, and 96 h) were separated among cultivars. MSC exhibited a greater difference than GRC between 24 and 48 h. The highest difference between cultivars was observed at the latest time point (i.e., 96 h), which agreed with the findings for TPC and TFC. The PCA-derived loadings plot revealed four features that influenced the discrimination of these GRC samples collected at later times (see Fig. 4c ). In order to evaluate the performance of these features over time, the dataset was analyzed through a multivariate empirical Bayes approach (MEBA) (
). This approach led us to rank the features by the differences in temporal profiles among cultivars according to the Hotelling-T2 values. The most-discriminating features selected by PCA for GRC (i.e., 42.4/579.1371, 61.8/582.1423, 43.1/801.2053, and 63.1/797.2114) were ranked by the highest Hotelling-T2 values ( > 105 ), which indicate that the time-course profiles of these features are more different between GRC and MSC cultivars ( Fig. 4d ). The behavior of these features was found to be different, showing a modest abundance at earlier times but increasing over time to reach the maximum values at 48 or 96 h, and showing a differential constitutive accumulation of these compounds between cultivars. This differential response showed a higher capacity to biosynthesize flavonoids at a constitutive level in the carnation resistant cultivar ‘
Golem
’ during the early times in the in vivo assay, so this fact will provide important insights into carnation plant selection based on discriminatory flavonoids (
;
).

sec.p:
Other features were also selected as important variables on the basis of the PCA- and MEBA-derived Hotelling-T2 values ( Fig. 4e ). From these important features, six flavonoids influenced the GRC discrimination maximally, whereas MSC was differentiated by the abundance of four flavonoids. These features showing the highest influence on discrimination of GRC and MSC , annotated at level 3 of MSI confidence as mentioned above, are listed in Table 1 . The annotated, statistically important glycosylated flavonoids 1–9 were found to be particularly related to the flavonol type , except flavone 10 . In particular, flavonol glycosides exhibited a structural trend based on a flavonoid aglycone (quercetin or kaempferol) attached to 1–3 sugar residues with an esterified group, except compounds 2, 3, and 7 . The presence of constitutive flavonols in these cultivars is a part of the metabolic characteristics of this plant species (
,
), since the distribution of some specific flavonoids at higher amounts in the resistant cultivar would support the hypothesis of their role in resistance (
;
,
). The most important flavonoids statistically ranked and selected in this study have not been previously described in carnation, except quercetin 3- O -α- L- arabinopyranosyl (1 → 6)-β- D- galactoside, which has the same aglycone and substitution pattern of the top-ranked compound 7 , a quercetin pentosyl-hexoside. The reported flavonol glycoside was previously detected in inter-node explants of ‘ Roland ’ resistant and ‘
Gloriana
’ susceptible carnation cultivars, and it proved to be slightly inhibitory toward the pathogen (
). This fact is in agreement with our findings, since the abundance of the glycosylated flavonoid 7 was greater in GRC than in MSC (although it occurred in both cultivars). Therefore, such GRC-abundant flavonoids (i.e., 2 , 5–9 ) are of interest since they may be involved in some role in the resistance against Fod . The antifungal activity of glycosylated flavonoids isolated from carnation has been previously reported. For instance, kaempferol 3- O -β- D- glucopyranosyl (1 → 2)- O -[α- L- rhamnopyranosyl-(1 → 6)]-β- D- glucopyranoside isolated from the ‘
Tirana
’ cultivar exhibited fungitoxic activity against Fod race 2 (
) and the kaempferide 3- O -[2 G- β- D- glucopyranosyl]-β- rutinoside, a constituent of the carnation cultivar ‘ Novada ’, was postulated to be a phytoanticipin (
) with a phytoalexin-like role, considering its levels during pathogen infection (
).

sec.title:
2.2.2.2. Metabolic profiling-based analysis of induced flavonoids associated with carnation defense against Fod.
Once resistant and susceptible cultivars were discriminated over time on the basis of constitutive flavonoids, the analysis was oriented to compare the flavonoid composition of Fod -inoculated and non-inoculated plants of both carnation cultivars at different post-inoculation times. Such a comparison was initially accomplished by two-factor clustering using Ward algorithm, whose intuitive visualization as a heat map is presented in Fig. 5a . The factors considered for this clustering were post-inoculation ‘time’ (12, 24, 48, and 96 hpi) and the plant ‘condition’ as primary ordering. In this case, the factor ‘condition’ refers to the combination of each cultivar ( GRC and MSC ) with and without Fod inoculation. Similar to the findings for the analysis of constitutive flavonoids ( Fig. 4a ), during this assay, GRC exhibited more flavonoid-related features with higher intensity than MSC , and 96 hpi also turned out to be the time that yielded the maximal number of higher-intensity features. The findings at 48 hpi also revealed other important features in GRC that were different from those of MSC . Additionally, Fod -inoculated GRC showed meaningful abundance differences from its control (non-inoculated plants), and these features also differed from those of MSC , indicating the induction of distinctive flavonoids between cultivars as a consequence of the Fod infection. Indeed, Ward clustering divided the dataset into two main groups according to the comparative metabolic distribution of each cultivar. However, the number of induced flavonoids in GRC was higher than those induced in MSC (See Fig. 5a ). Therefore, in order to explore the major patterns associated with each factor, an ANOVA-simultaneous component analysis (ASCA) (
) was employed on a flavonoid-filtered FIT dataset. This algorithm first splits the overall data variance into individual variances induced by each factor (i.e., “time” and “condition”), as well as by one interaction (i.e., “time × condition”), and the major variations in each partition are summarized by a PCA applied to individual factors and interaction. The resulting models (see Fig. 5b ) illustrated the score variations associated with the factors “condition” and “time” on the first component, which explained 87.7% and 68.2% of the variation, respectively. The model of the factor “condition” ( Figs. 5b – 1 ) indicated that the highest variations were presented in Fod -inoculated GRC , being oppositely different to that of MSC , as noticed in the previous two-factor clustering. Furthermore, flavonoid induction was more evident in the inoculated GRC in comparison to the control, so the Fod -related response of GRC can be considered to be higher. On the other hand, the “time” factor-related model ( Figs. 5b – 2 ) revealed a time-dependent behavior of the variations. This finding suggested that variations between cultivars and inoculation regarding control is enhanced over time, reaching a statistically important maximum variation at 96 hpi. The “time × condition” interaction-derived submodels on the first component (which explained 41.5% of the variation) confirmed the behavior observed for individual factors, since the highest variations were caused by inoculated GRC ( Figs. 5c – 3 ) and 96 hpi ( Figs. 5c – 1 ) in comparison to the other conditions and times. MSC exhibited decreasing variation, implying a lower flavonoid-related response against Fod, possibly as part of the susceptibility phenotype related to the higher disease progression ( Fig. 2 ). The same interaction scores for the second component (28.2% of variation explained) exhibited a second behavior involving the highest variations at 48 hpi by inoculated GRC , which is in agreement with the enhanced accumulation over time. Under this context, the resistant cultivar exhibited the highest time-course response for flavonoid accumulation caused by Fod inoculation, and 96 hpi appeared to be the time point with the highest response at root level.

sec.p:
To elucidate these findings, a dual comparison between Fod -inoculated and non-inoculated plants of carnation GRC at 96 hpi was carried out to identify the features that influence the discrimination of such a condition. Thus, the ten top-ranked features by an unpaired parametric t -test exhibited four compounds previously related to constitutive levels ( 4 , 5 , 6 , 7 ) and six other flavonoids that were not ranked in the previous analysis related to constitutive metabolites ( 11–16 ) ( Fig. 6a ). Two flavonoids ( 5 , 16 ) were selected to be related to GRC control and the remaining eight top-ranked flavonoids were important for inoculated GRC ( 4 , 7 , 11–15 ); therefore, these last flavonoids were considered to show a possible association with pathogen resistance. Among these compounds, a flavonoid ( 12 ) was annotated at MSI level 4 of confidence since the diagnostic evidence was not useful to clarify a higher annotation level and the type of flavonoid was deduced by the UV bands ( Table 1 ), whereas compounds 11 , 13, and 15 exhibited the same structural pattern as the top-ranked constitutive flavonoids (i.e., an aglycone attached to pentose or hexose residues with an ester substitution), even flavone 14 . On the other hand, three glycosides ( 6 , 7 , 11 ) showed the lowest P-values (-log 10 (raw P-value) > 6), so their fold changes in comparison with the control could be interpreted as indicating that these were the most induced flavonoids by Fod inoculation in the resistant cultivar. Compounds 6–7 (previously found to be as constitutively abundant flavonoids in GRC ) are significantly induced by Fod inoculation, and compound 11 , which was constitutively expressed in lower amounts, is also largely induced. These observations, as well as the classification model performance, were demonstrated and validated by classical receiver operating characteristic ( ROC ) curves under the same dual inoculation comparison ( Fig. 6b ). For these three t -testderived top-ranked flavonoids, the area under the curve (AUC) was found to be 1 with high FC values ( > 2). The mean distribution and optimal cutoffs between Fod -inoculated and non-inoculated group samples were additionally very dissimilar according to the respective box-plots ( Fig. 6b ). The MEBA-derived time-course profiles also confirmed our findings, exhibiting significant abundance increments at 96 hpi for Fod -inoculated GRC roots ( Fig. 6c ). On the findings for constitutive and induced expression, flavonoids 6 (even 4 ) and 11 can be proposed as phytoanticipin and/or phytoalexin-like candidates, respectively, since kaempferol derivatives have exhibited biological activity against Fod (
) and other phytopathogens (Gorniak´et al., 2019). However, this hypothesis requires additional studies to demonstrate such a role against this pathogen (e.g., fungitoxic activity). In addition, flavonols can act as antioxidants and can function as direct scavengers of reactive oxygen species (ROS), in addition to their functions in activation of antioxidant enzymes and/or inhibition of oxidases (
;
), and they are related to resistance against nechotrophic and hemibiotrhophic pathogens (
;
;
).

The transcriptional constitutive levels of putative fls ( Dca12008.1 gene) in GRC were found to be significantly higher than those in the susceptible cultivar ( Fig. 7c ). These levels in the Fod -inoculated GRC particularly increased at 24 and 96 hpi in comparison to the control, whereas MSC roots only exhibited a difference between control and inoculated samples at 24 hpi. The higher mRNA levels of fls in the resistant cultivar may be associated with the aforementioned abundance of flavonols (
;
;
). However, increased transcription of the fls gene was found to occur earlier than those of the chs and chi genes (i.e., from 24 hpi in GRC ), which can be also associated with the accumulation of certain flavonoids at 48 hpi ( Figs. 4–6 ) and an early response through production of flavonols that, due to their antioxidant capacity, would present a quick counteracting effect against the elevated ROS levels caused by the pathogen recognition (
).

Regarding transcriptional levels of the putative cmyb11 gene ( Dca2677.1 ) coding for the TF cMYB, both cultivars showed significant differences between the constitutive levels and those derived at 12 hpi and 48 hpi after Fod inoculation. In contrast, no significant differences were observed between the controls and inoculated plants at 24 hpi. Although 48 hpi represents a reasonably prompt response against
Fusarium
pathogens (
;
), GRC exhibited an earlier response based on the significant increase in cmyb11 levels at 12 hpi. These results suggest that this Dca26277.1-encoded TF may be involved in the gene regulatory processes for flavonoid biosynthesis. Thus, the joint activation of this gene with other genes coding for TFs of chs , chi , f3h , and fls (
) could be considered as a part of the molecular mechanism related to the polygenic mechanisms against Fod , particularly emphasizing the essential regulatory role of the phenylpropanoid pathway in plant
resistance ( Desmedt et al., 2021 )
.

A Pearson correlation analysis was eventually employed to compare the test flavonoid biosynthesis-related parameters ( Table 2 ). A positive correlation was found between TFC and the transcriptional levels of chs (0.56, α = 0.05 ), as well as the transcriptional levels of chi and chs (0.95, α = 0.05 ) and the mRNA encoding the TF MYB11. Flavonoid biosynthesis in carnation roots can be considered to be a transcriptionally regulated complex process. However, the total content and semiquantitative levels of flavonoids in carnation roots were related to the transcriptional increase in the genes encoding CHI, CHS, and FLS enzymes, which are particularly important for flavonoid accumulation in plants (
;
). We suggest that the transcriptional activation of the chs , chi , and fls genes is a part of the complex response related to the innate resistance mechanisms for recognizing MAMPs (microbe-associated molecular patterns) conserved in
Fusarium
genus. The changes in the ROS levels caused by pathogen recognition may generate the activation of MYB TFs, which have been reported to be associated with transcriptional activation of flavonoid biosynthesis enzymes (
;
). It is likely that the increase in H 2 O 2 content during Fod inoculation activates these carnation MYB TFs to increase the transcriptional levels of the genes encoding flavonoid biosynthesis enzymes. Thus, our findings indicate the influence of the protein cMYB11 on flavonoid biosynthesis in carnation roots, consistent with the regulatory role of myb11 over chs and chi genes (
;
). This fact coincides with the polygenic nature of carnation resistance against race 2 of this pathogen (
;
).

Our findings yielded some insights involving flavonoid biosynthesis in the resistance response against Fod in carnation roots. Pathogen recognition occurred in the early phase, as previously reported for this pathosystem (
). This recognition triggered signaling toward the cellular nucleus and induced increased cmyb gene transcription at 12 hpi ( Fig. 7d ). Elevated protein levels of the cMYB TF enhanced the promoter activity of chi and chs genes and favored the increase in the mRNA levels of these genes at 24 hpi ( Fig. 7a and b ). Higher transcriptional levels of chs and chi led to increased CHI and CHS enzyme activity in the endoplasmic reticulum, where flavonoid biosynthesis occurs (
;
). Subsequently, the mRNA level of the fls gene increased at 48 hpi, which, in turn, enhanced the levels of this protein. Glucosyltransferase (GTF) enzymes are estimated to be important during flavonoid synthesis, as previously described, mainly in relation to the accumulation and transport of these compounds (
). Finally, certain acylglycosylated kaempferol-like flavonoids (such as 4 , 6 , 11 ) will accumulate at 96 hpi, mostly in vacuoles (
). The final localization of the accumulated flavonoids during infection should be in the apoplast, and their action would be related to its antioxidant and/or antifungal activity against Fod (
,
;
). In summary, the early phase of flavonoid biosynthesis in both carnation cultivars was perturbed differentially by the presence of Fod , and involved the accumulation of certain flavonols and the temporal transcriptional upregulation of MYB11 TF, CHI, CHS, and FLS enzymes from 12 to 96 hpi. The temporal variations of these components during Fod infection support the events related to the early flavonoid biosynthesis-based response as a resistance trait of carnation against the hemibiotrophic pathogen
Fusarium oxysporum
f. sp. dianthi ( Fod ) race 2.

Inoculation with a pathogenic isolate of Fod was carried out according to the previous study (
). A total of 300 rooted cuttings of each cultivar ( GRC and MSC ) were inoculated by immersion of the roots into the pathogen suspension for 20 s. Simultaneously, 300 cuttings of each cultivar were subjected to the same process using sterile water instead of conidial suspension. Under a randomized 2 × 2 × 4 × 3 experimental design (i.e., cultivars × Fod - and non-inoculated × sampling times × triplicate), cuttings were planted independently for each treatment, in a 50/50 mixture of sterilized soil and rice hulls. The inoculated and control cuttings were harvested at 12, 24, 48, and 96 h after inoculation, according to previous results describing early responses associated to resistance in this pathosystem (
). For each time, three biological replicates consisted of 25 cuttings per treatment were used. The samples were washed with water to remove soil excess, and stems and roots were separated and kept at

Total phenolic content (TPC) were measured using the Folin–Ciocalteu method (

) with slight modifications. Each reaction mixture contained 20 μL of the methanolic extracts and 40 μL of the Folin–Ciocalteu. After 5 min, 150 μL of 7.35% Na 
2
CO 
3
