After LC-HRMS analyses, HRMS-derived features were recovered from raw profiles using MZmine 2 and following a previous procedure for feature filtering (

). Detected features were listed and labelled with the respective retention time/(- mass/charge) ratio (rt/ 
m/z
) pairs. After a detailed scrutiny of the combined LC-DAD, LC-MS and LC-HRMS data, HRMS-features were filtered to gather specifically the flavonoid-like metabolites according to the typical flavonoid bands I and II (i.e., 270–295 and 
310–350 nm
, respectively) in the UV spectra (see 
Table 1
). Once features were filtered, peak annotation procedure led to characterize metabolites into the categories such as unequivocal molecular formula (level 4) or tentative candidates (level 3), following the confidence levels of the metabolomics standard initiative (MSI) (

). The MSI level 1 (confirmed structure) and 2 (probable structure) were not possible to be reached in this study due to a lack of authentic standards and/or enough information using only HRMS to propose a unique structure (e.g., exact isomer of sugar residues) of the conjugated specialized metabolites detected, filtered and processed. Molecular formulas were predominantly deduced from the accurate mass of the quasi-molecular ion obtained in negative ion mode ([M+ H] 
-
). Feature annotation was therefore achieved by the combined diagnostic of the accurate mass errors (in ppm) and the typical MS fragments, supported by phylogenetic filtering, chromatographic behavior (if possible) and data comparison with different databases (e.g., dictionary of natural products, Metlin, KNApSAcK, PubChem).

Transcriptional levels of putative genes encoding CHS, CHI, FLS, and MYB TF were evaluated according to the previous study using a relative quantification to histone (
). To obtain the RNA extracts, carnation roots were macerated using liquid nitrogen in a mortar previously washed with a DEPC (diethylpyrocarbonate) solution. Extraction was performed with 0.4 g of the macerated material using Trizol (Invitrogen) according to the supplier’ s instructions. The RNA in the samples was quantified by absorbance readings at 260 nm . The A260/A280 ratio ranged from 1.9 to 2.0. To avoid contamination with DNA, 2 μg of the total RNA sample was treated with DNase (Invitrogen) under the conditions recommended by the supplier. The synthesis of cDNA from RNA was subsequently performed using oligo dT and M-MLV reverse transcriptase (Moloney murine leukemia virus, Invitrogen) according to the manufacturer’ s protocol. The transcriptional levels quantification was performed using the system SYBR® Green MasterMix IQTM, Bio-Rad. To ensure that the same amount of cDNA was used in each reaction ( 10 ng ), the cDNA amount was quantified by fluorescence (Qbit®, Invitrogen). The primers used for amplification of the chs , chi , fls , and myb11 genes are listed in Table 3 . Primers of CHS and CHI were designed according to the sequences reported previously (
). For histone was used the primers described by
, and for fls and myb11, primers were designed using the Genome of Carnation database (ID fls : Dca12008.1 and gen ID cmyb11 : Dca26277.1). Amplification of chs y chi genes was performed using an initial denaturation at 95 ◦ C for 10 min followed by 35 cycles at 95 ◦ C (15 s), 60 ◦ C (20 s), and 72 ◦ C (20 s) and finally 72 ◦ C (1 min). For the fls , myb11 and histone genes, a modification was made, using an initial denaturation at 95 ◦ C for 10 min followed by 35 cycles at 95 ◦ C (15 s), 59 ◦ C (20 s) and 72 ◦ C (20 s) and finally 72 ◦ C (1 min). The specificity of the products was validated by analyzing the melting curves. The analysis was performed using a C1000 Thermal cycler coupled to a Bio-Rad CFX96 real-time system. The quantification was performed by comparing the values of Ct (threshold cycle) obtained for the different treatments and those obtained by the reference gene using the following formula: ( E 1)
Δ CPtarget ( control sample )
) / ( E 2)
Δ CPref ( control sample )
, where E2 = target gen and E1 = reference gen (
).

Statistical analysis was performed for each variable for the different treatments (n = 3). Data were expressed as means ± standard deviations (SD) or SEM. The analysis of variance and differences between means were analyzed using the Statgraphics® software version 5.1 with oneway ANOVA and Tukey test (
P
˂ 0.05
). Pearson’ s correlation ( α = 0.05 ) was done using the software IBM SPSS Statistics v22.0. Furthermore, major patterns and important features from flavonoid-related metabolic profiles were obtained and described by univariate and multivariate statistics, using unpaired parametric t -test, PCA, ASCA, MEBA and ROC approaches. These analyses were performed after recovery of the peak intensity of each m/z feature present in each of the negative mode ionization-derived total ion current (TIC) chromatograms. These HRMS features were compiled under processing of the whole set of the raw TICs with MZmine 2 (
), through the typical steps of normalization, signal detection, deconvolution, deisotopization, filtering, alignment, and gap-filling. As mentioned above, under comparison of LC-PDA data, the flavonoid-related compounds were filtered. The resulting matrix (FIT) corresponding to the combination of Observations (i.e., samples) versus Variables (i.e., features labelled as rt/ m/z pairs) was exported to.csv format and statistically analyzed through the different modules of MetaboAnalyst 4.0 (McGill University, Quebec , Canada ).
